  "title": "Euler‚Äôs Method",
  "body": " Euler's Method   We've explored what linear systems are, how to visualize their behavior, and even how to write them neatly in vector form. Now it's time to start solving them.  We'll begin with the classic trick that worked for single equations ‚Äî guessing exponential solutions ‚Äî then finish by showing how to approximate solutions step by step with a numerical method.    Numerical Solutions for Linear Systems  Not every system is easy to solve exactly. Sometimes, you just want to see what the solution looks like ‚Äî or approximate it for a while. That's where numerical methods shine.  One of the simplest is Euler's Method , which you've seen for single equations. We'll now apply it to systems.  Suppose we have:   With initial conditions , , and a step size of .   Euler's Method for a System   Use Euler's method to take two steps for the system above.     Step 1: At , we have , . The derivatives are , .  Update:    Step 2: At , we have , . Now , .  Update again:   We now have approximate values after two steps:   Each step shows how and  talk to each other as time progresses.    Euler's Method may be simple, but it makes the flow of information between variables visible: each update for affects on the next step, and vice versa.    ü§îüí≠ Numerical Solutions for Linear Systems Reading Questions   ü§îüí≠ Numerical Methods for Systems   Euler's Method Thinking   What does Euler's Method do when applied to a system of DEs?     It updates each variable step by step using its derivative at the current point.    It shows how the variables influence each other from one step to the next.    It provides the exact solution in one step.  Euler's Method is an approximation technique, not an exact one-step solution.    It can only be used for uncoupled systems.  Euler's Method works for any system, coupled or not.      Interpreting Numerical Results   When we use Euler's Method on a system, what do the computed points represent?     They are approximate values of the solution at specific time steps.    They are exact values that replace the need for solving the system algebraically.  They're approximate ‚Äî we still use exact methods when possible.    They are estimates of the system's coefficients.  Euler's Method updates and , not the coefficients.       "
